| Trivia                  = * The Sakaaran soldiers that appear in the film were originally supposed to be the [[Badoon]].{{cite|ref=true|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/exclusive-james-gunn-says-planet-hulk-guardians-of-the-galaxy-rumors-are-a-bunch-of-complete-b-llshit-20140721|title=Exclusive: James Gunn Says 'Planet Hulk'/'Guardians of the Galaxy' Rumors Are "A Bunch Of Complete Bullsh*t"|last=Taylor|first=Drew|work=The Playlist|date=21 July 2014|accessdate=21 July 2014}}
* The name of Peter Quill’s ship, The ''Milano'', is a tribute to his childhood crush {{WP|Alyssa Milano}}.
* The contents of Peter’s backpack, which show up at various times in the film, include such '80s-kid staples as Garbage Pail Kid cards and a troll doll.
* Peter refers to the orb as having a "shiny suitcase, Ark of the Covenant, Maltese Falcon vibe." This is a reference to the films ''{{WP|Kiss Me Deadly}}'', ''{{WP|The Maltese Falcon (1941 film)|The Maltese Falcon}}'' and ''{{WP|Raiders of the Lost Ark}}''.
* The scene in which Groot gives a small girl a flower was inspired by a similar scene (with a much different outcome) from {{WP|James Whale}}'s 1931 film ''{{WP|Frankenstein (1931 film)|Frankenstein}}''.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.cbr.com/groot-guardians-galaxy-frankenstein/|title=Gunn Confirms the Inspiration for GotG’s Groot Flower Scene|work=CBR.com|first=Renaldo|last=Matadeen|date=14 May 2018|accessdate=17 May 2018}}
* [[Stan Lee]] was originally going to appear as one of the specimens in the Collector's museum, with the legendary creator "flipping off" Groot from inside a display case. As Stan Lee wasn't able to come the United Kingdom at that time, a double was going to be used, and had his face digitally replaced with Lee's. However, "a couple of guys at Marvel" thought Stan Lee in a case was too broad of a joke in general, and that it would've taken the audience out of the movie, so after an argument with James Gunn, the scene was removed from the film's final cut. Additionally, James Gunn thought the scene would've been too similar to Star-Lord flipping off the Nova Corps.{{cite|ref=true|url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=55289|title=Gunn Reveals Stan Lee's Original "Guardians of the Galaxy" Cameo|first=Steve|last=Sunu|work=Comic Book Resources|date=4 September 2014|accessdate=4 September 2014}}
* At the very end of the credit scroll is the line "No raccoons or tree creatures were harmed in the making of this film."

